Irish Echo Photographs

Contents

Series I. Irish America, 1936-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This series comprises the bulk of the collection and consists primarily of photographic prints of various sizes. The contents of this series document Irish American social organizations, political figures and activities, and sporting events, mostly in the greater New York City area. Although some photographs in this series date back to the 1930s and 1940s, the majority of images featured in this series were taken after 1950. This series contains photographs documenting the intersection of the Irish influence on American culture, and is further divided into four subseries.

Subseries I.A. Organizations: General, 1937-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries contains photographs of various Irish American organizations and events in the United States. A large number of these photographs document County Societies' functions, banquets, and award ceremonies during the 1970s and 1980s. Other major subjects include Irish American educational institutions and charitable organizations.

Subseries I.B. Politics, 1966-2001.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries contains photographs of politically-affiliated Irish American causes, events, and organizations, including photographs documenting efforts made in the United States on behalf of the peace process in Northern Ireland. Common subjects include relief efforts, the 1981 Hunger Strike, and prisoner treatment with overarching themes of Irish unity and solidarity. Politicians who held office in Ireland and/or the United States can be found in Series II. Ireland: Subseries A. Politics and Series III. United States: Subseries B. Politics, respectively.

Subseries I.C. Subjects, circa 1930-1936, 1967-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries encompasses a range of topics relevant to The Irish Echo's primary readership base: Irish Americans and Irish in America. In addition to subjects covered extensively, such as dance, festivals, and St. Patrick's Day Parades, this subseries also includes a significant number of photographs taken in historically Irish American communities throughout New York City and State. Photographs taken outside of New York are organized by state name followed by additional parenthetical identifiers whenever possible.

Series II. Ireland, 1959-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This series consists of photographic prints of various sizes, all of which were taken in The Republic of Ireland or Northern Ireland over a period of approximately 65 years. The photographs contained in this series document tourism and tourist attractions in almost all of the Irish counties; major Irish businesses and business leaders; Irish politicians; and Irish athletes and the athletic events. This series contains photographs documenting key aspects of Irish life and is further divided into four subseries.

Subseries II.A. Tourism, 1957-2003.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries is comprised largely of scenic photographs taken in many of the Irish counties. Specific tourist destinations are organized by type, such as churches or pubs.

Subseries II.C. Politics, 1959-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries contains photographs of influential politicians from both the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland. Included in this subseries are Sinn Féin President Gerry Adams, former Social Democratic and Labour Party leader John Hume, Presidents of Ireland Éamon de Valera and Mary Robinson, and former Taoisigh Bertie Ahern and Séan Lemass. Other noteworthy individuals appearing in this series include former British Prime Ministers Tony Blair and Margaret Thatcher.

Arrangement

This subseries features images of Irish politicians organized alphabetically by surname; minor politicians, as well as prominent politicians with limited documentation, are featured in the alphabetic sequence prefaced by "Individual Politicians" and followed by a letter.

Series III. United States, 1940-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This series consists of photographic prints of various sizes. Photos in this series depict American businesses and politicians, as well as sports and athletes that were once the subject of the newspaper's reporting. Noteworthy subjects featured in this series include substantial documentation of Irish restaurants and pubs in America and an approximately 65-year photographic history of New York City's leading politicians. This series is divided into four subseries.

Subseries III.B. Politics, 1940-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries contains photographs of influential American politicians at every level of government, from City Councilmen to President. The politicians in these photos represent a range of ethnic backgrounds over approximately sixty years. The earliest photos in this subseries are of New York City politicians during the 1960s and 1970s, including images of former Mayor William O'Dwyer, a native of Co. Mayo, and of New York State Senator Robert F. Wagner. Also included in this subseries are topical headings, such as "State Politics" and "Women in Politics." An individual's folder, such as Joe Crowley, and a topical folder, like "State Politics," are not mutually exclusive.

Series V. Artists, circa 1938-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

Because of the fluidity and significance of cultural exchange between communities in Ireland and the United States, this series consists of photographic prints of both Irish and Irish American performers. Notable artists and bands featured in this series include playwright Seamus Heaney, authors Maeve Binchy and Frank McCourt, and musical groups such as The Chieftains and U2. Photographs documenting productions or adaptations of these artists and others are featured in Series VI. Film, Television, Theatre. This series is divided into two subseries.

Arrangement

Contained in this series are two subseries, both of which are organized alphabetically according to artists' surnames or band name. Major artists and bands are listed individually. Lesser known artists and bands are featured in alphabetic sequences prefaced by "Individual Artists" or "General Bands," and then followed by a letter.

Subseries V.A. Individual Artists, 1925-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries primarily consists of photographs of Irish and Irish American actors, actresses, writers, musicians, and other performers. Some American artists with ties to the Irish American or Irish communities are also featured. The majority of these photographs are official headshots or taken on location.

31142054612133box: 9, folder: 101 (Material Type: photographs)

Subseries V.B. Bands, 1960-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries mainly contains photographs of traditional Irish showbands, as well as more contemporary Irish and Irish American bands. Some unaffiliated but extremely influential bands, such as The Beatles, are also included. Noteworthy bands featured in this subseries include The Chieftains, The Dubliners, The Irish Rovers, The Saw Doctors, and U2. The majority of these photos are bands' official publicity shots.

Series VI. Film, Television, and Theatre, 1952, 1970-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This series is comprised primarily of photographic prints from American and Irish film, television, and theatre that were advertised or otherwise featured in The Irish Echo. The majority of photos in this series are either official publicity shots distributed by production studios or snapshots taken on set. This series is further divided into two subseries.

Arrangement

This series contains two subseries, both of which are organized alphabetically according to production title. Major works are listed individually. Less prominent films, television shows, and theatrical productions are featured in alphabetic sequences prefaced by "Film and Television" or "Theatre," and then followed by a letter.

Subseries VI.A. Film and Television, 1952, 1970-2001.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries consists of photographic prints of popular Irish, American, and Irish American films and television, such as My Left Foot and In The Name of the Father, both of which were directed by Irish filmmaker Jim Sheridan. Also included are photographs from a variety of popular or successful American productions, as well as smaller independent pictures, such as The Secret of Roan Inish. The majority of photographs featured in this subseries are from the 1990s and early 2000s.

Subseries VI.B. Theatre, 1970-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This subseries consists of photographic prints of popular Irish and Irish American theatre productions staged in Ireland, primarily Dublin, and in the United States, primarily New York. Featured in this subseries are photographs of significant works including Martin McDonagh's The Beauty Queen of Leenane, Samuel Beckett's Waiting for Godot, and Brian Friel's Dancing at Lughnasa. Photographs of several Shakespearean productions, including Hamlet, King Lear, and A Midsummer's Night Dream, are also included. The majority of photographs featured in this subseries were taken between 1980 and the early 2000s.

Series VII. Individuals, circa 1960-2004.,

Scope and Content Note

This series consists of photographic prints of various Irish, American, and Irish American individuals. Included in this series is extensive photographic documentation of Roman Catholic clergy from all levels of rank. Additionally, this series features individuals who resist strictly defined categorization (either by qualifying for multiple categories or for none at all) and who can be regarded more generally as public figures of varying degrees of importance. One example is the late Connie Doolan, a celebrated Irish immigration activist; former New York imports representative for Guinness; and a highly successful businessman. Rather than constrain him to a single identifying characteristic, as is the structure for Series I-VI, Doolan is featured in Series VII. Another example is that of Veronica Guerin, who was both a journalist and an activist, and thus is also featured in Series VII.

Arrangement

This series is unique to the rest of the collection in terms of its ordering scheme. Series VII follows a strict alphabetical arrangement with a general alphabetic sequence dispersed throughout, rather than clustered. For example, following the general "A" folder are the folders for promiment individuals with surnames beginning in A; following that is the general "B" folder and then folders for prominent individuals with surnames beginning in B, continuing through "Z".
